## Drop dev-app/ wrapper â€” auto-detect app name at runtime

Context: the previous "Carve ontobricks-dev into its own DAB" change
introduced a small ``dev-app/`` directory that held a sandbox-specific
``app.yaml`` plus symlinks to the real source tree. Its only reason to
exist was to override the single env var ``ONTOBRICKS_APP_NAME`` so the
sandbox app would identify itself as ``ontobricks-dev`` (instead of
``ontobricks``) in permission lookups. Since the new
``ontobricks_dev_bundle`` only manages one app, the "duplicate
``source_code_path``" rule that originally forced the wrapper no longer
applies. We can ship the dev sandbox straight from the repo root and
let it auto-detect its own name from the Databricks Apps runtime.

Changes:

1. src/shared/config/settings.py
   - ``Settings.ontobricks_app_name`` now uses
     ``Field(validation_alias=AliasChoices("ONTOBRICKS_APP_NAME",
     "DATABRICKS_APP_NAME"))``. Pydantic-settings tries the explicit
     override first, then falls back to the platform-injected
     ``DATABRICKS_APP_NAME`` (the Databricks Apps runtime sets it to
     the deployed app's name automatically â€” ``ontobricks`` for prod,
     ``ontobricks-dev`` for the sandbox).
   - Doc-comment on the field now describes the alias chain.

2. app.yaml (repo root)
   - Removed the explicit ``ONTOBRICKS_APP_NAME: ontobricks`` block.
     Functionally a no-op for the production app: the auto-injected
     ``DATABRICKS_APP_NAME`` resolves to ``ontobricks`` for it, so the
     permission service still queries the correct ACL.
   - The new comment explains the auto-detection contract and points
     out that ``.env`` can still set the var explicitly for local dev.

3. databricks.yml
   - ``ontobricks_dev_app.source_code_path`` switched from
     ``./dev-app`` to ``.`` (the repository root). One app per bundle
     means we no longer need a wrapper directory to satisfy the
     duplicate-path constraint.
   - Updated the header doc-comment to describe the auto-detection
     of the sandbox name and to drop the ``dev-app/`` reference.

4. dev-app/
   - Removed in its entirety (sandbox ``app.yaml`` + symlinks to the
     source tree). The bundle now ships the same source the prod app
     ships from, with target-specific behaviour driven by env vars
     and the DAB resource bindings only.

5. docs/deployment.md
   - Removed ``ONTOBRICKS_APP_NAME`` from the "workspace-specific
     values" table; replaced with a callout describing the
     auto-detection.
   - In the annotated ``app.yaml`` sample, removed the explicit
     ``ONTOBRICKS_APP_NAME`` entry and replaced it with a comment
     pointing at the alias chain.

6. docs/development.md
   - Permission appendix: ``ONTOBRICKS_APP_NAME`` is now marked as
     optional, with the auto-detection explanation.

Verification:

* ``uv run pytest -q`` â€” full suite green (1808 passed in 60s). The
  config / auth tests in particular exercise ``Settings`` loading and
  the Databricks-Apps-mode detection.
* ``ls dev-app/`` returns "No such file or directory".
* ``databricks bundle validate -t dev`` and ``-t dev-lakebase`` still
  resolve cleanly from the repo root (run separately).

Operational notes:

* The production ``ontobricks`` app is **not redeployed** by this
  change. Its currently-running container still has
  ``ONTOBRICKS_APP_NAME=ontobricks`` set from its previous deploy.
  Whenever it next gets redeployed (from a future bundle bound to it,
  not this one) it will pick up the new ``app.yaml`` and rely on the
  auto-injected ``DATABRICKS_APP_NAME`` instead â€” same value, same
  behaviour.
* For local development without ``.env``, set
  ``ONTOBRICKS_APP_NAME`` explicitly (no Databricks Apps runtime to
  auto-inject the fallback).


================================================================
[Settings] Lakebase: database picker for the Registry Location
================================================================

Context:
The Registry Location modal could only edit the Postgres *schema*.
The actual database the Lakebase backend talked to was always the
one auto-injected via ``PGDATABASE`` from the Apps ``database``
resource binding (e.g. ``ontobricks_registry``), so the only way
to point the registry at a *different* database was to redeploy
the bundle. With multiple databases now living on the same
Lakebase instance, admins want to switch between them at runtime.

Decision:
The Lakebase JWT scope is per-instance â€” the cached token can
authenticate against every database on the same instance the SP
is allowed on. We therefore expose a per-registry override
(``lakebase_database``) that lives next to ``lakebase_schema`` in
the global config; when set, the store overrides ``dbname`` in
the psycopg conninfo. When empty, it falls back to ``PGDATABASE``
exactly like before.

The override is keyed into the connection pool so swapping it
spins up a new pool against the new database without recycling
existing connections (a single Postgres connection only ever talks
to a single database, so we cannot reuse them anyway).

Changes:

1. src/back/objects/registry/RegistryService.py
   - ``RegistryCfg`` gains ``lakebase_database: str = ""``.
   - ``from_volume_path`` / ``from_domain`` / ``from_dict`` /
     ``as_dict`` plumb the new field. Defaults preserve the old
     behaviour (empty = "use PGDATABASE").

2. src/shared/config/settings.py
   - ``Settings.lakebase_database`` is the env-level fallback for
     the override (rare; mostly there for test parity).

3. src/back/objects/registry/store/lakebase/store.py
   - ``LakebaseRegistryStore`` accepts ``database=`` and stores it
     alongside ``schema``.
   - ``_LakebasePool`` accepts ``database=`` and overrides
     ``dbname`` in ``self._auth.kwargs(...)`` when opening a
     connection.
   - ``_get_pool`` keys on ``(host, port, bound_db, effective_db,
     user, instance, schema)`` so each (database, schema) pair
     gets its own pool.
   - ``cache_key`` and ``describe()`` now expose ``effective_database``
     and ``database_override`` so the registry-cache TTL bucket is
     invalidated automatically on switch.

4. src/back/objects/registry/store/factory.py
   - ``RegistryFactory.lakebase`` / ``for_backend`` / ``from_cfg``
     accept ``database=`` / ``lakebase_database=`` and forward it
     to the store. ``build_store`` legacy alias updated too.

5. src/back/objects/domain/SettingsService.py
   - New module-level ``_SAFE_DBNAME_RE``: validates the override
     against ``[A-Za-z_][A-Za-z0-9_-]*`` to keep dynamic SQL safe.
   - ``apply_registry_save`` accepts ``lakebase_database``. An
     empty string in the payload clears the override.
   - ``_lakebase_runtime_info`` returns ``database`` (bound),
     ``database_override`` (admin choice) and ``effective_database``
     (whichever is in use).
   - ``lakebase_stats_result`` and ``migrate_to_lakebase_result``
     pass ``cfg.lakebase_database`` through to
     ``RegistryFactory.lakebase``.
   - New ``list_lakebase_databases_result`` helper:
     connects to the bound database, runs
     ``SELECT datname, has_database_privilege(...)`` against
     ``pg_database`` and returns ``[{name, connectable, is_bound,
     is_selected}, ...]``. Filters out ``postgres`` / ``rdsadmin``
     / template DBs.

6. src/api/routers/internal/settings.py
   - New admin-only ``GET /settings/registry/lakebase-databases``
     endpoint that calls ``list_lakebase_databases_result``.

7. src/front/templates/partials/registry/_registry_configuration.html
   - Read-only "Database" field renamed to "Database (effective)"
     with a hint line that flips between *override* and
     *from app resource binding*.
   - Modal: new ``Lakebase Database`` ``<select>`` shown only when
     the backend is Lakebase. First option is "default â€” use bound
     database"; the rest are populated dynamically.

8. src/front/static/registry/js/registry.js
   - ``updateLakebasePanel`` renders the effective DB and the
     override hint.
   - ``updateRegistryLabel`` adds an ``override`` badge when the
     selected DB differs from the bound one.
   - New ``loadModalLakebaseDatabases``: fetches the new endpoint,
     renders selectable options (disables ones the SP cannot
     CONNECT to, marks the bound one), preselects the current
     override, and degrades gracefully on API errors.
   - Apply button POSTs ``lakebase_database`` alongside the
     existing fields.

9. tests/test_registry.py
   - Added ``"lakebase_database": ""`` to the ``_make_settings``
     defaults and the ``as_dict`` golden so the new field is
     exercised by the existing roundtrip + factory tests.

Verification:

* ``uv run pytest -q`` â€” 1808 passed in 61s.
* Linter clean across the touched modules.
* The change is fully backwards compatible â€” existing deployments
  see ``lakebase_database=""`` and behave identically to before.

================================================================
[Registry] Auto-refresh the Browse list on sidebar nav
================================================================

Bug:
On the Registry page, switching to Bridges (or any other sidebar
section) and coming back to **Browse** (the Domains panel) left
the table showing whatever was loaded on first page-render. New
versions, freshly-activated versions, deletes, or a backend /
Lakebase-database switch in Settings were never reflected until
the user clicked the small refresh button in the panel header.

Root cause:
``sidebar-nav.js`` dispatches a ``sidebarSectionChanged`` event on
every nav-link click. ``registry.js`` only listened for it on the
``bridges`` section (lazy-load). The ``domains`` section had no
listener, so navigating back never re-fetched.

Fix:
``src/front/static/registry/js/registry.js`` â€” extended the
``sidebarSectionChanged`` handler with a ``domains`` branch that
calls ``loadRegistryDomains()`` whenever the user navigates back
to the Browse panel. Guarded by ``registryConfigured`` so we
don't hammer the API while the registry is still being set up
(the initial ``loadRegistryConfig`` already primes the list once
the registry is ready).

Verification:
* Linter clean.
* Manual: open Registry, click Bridges, click Domains â€” list
  re-fetches without pressing the refresh button. The refresh
  button still works as before.

================================================================
[bug] Registry/Browse silently ignored Lakebase database override
================================================================

Bug:
After picking *Lakebase* (and optionally a non-default database)
in **Settings â†’ Registry Location**, the Registry/Browse panel
still listed domains. The list looked correct on a fresh deploy
where ``cfg.lakebase_database`` is empty (so the bound
``PGDATABASE`` is used anyway), but as soon as the admin used
the new database picker to point the registry at a *different*
Postgres database on the same Lakebase instance, Browse kept
reading from the old, bound database. Migration / Initialize
already honoured the override (they go through the
``SettingsService`` helpers which were updated when the picker
landed) â€” only the read path used by Browse was broken.

Root cause:
Every read path used by the Registry/Browse UI ultimately goes
through ``RegistryService.from_context(domain, settings)`` â†’
``RegistryService.__init__`` â†’ ``RegistryService._build_store``.
That helper hand-built the Lakebase store via
``RegistryFactory.lakebase(registry_cfg=cfg, schema=cfg.lakebase_schema)``
and forgot to forward ``database=cfg.lakebase_database``. The
factory then defaulted to the bound ``PGDATABASE`` so the store
connected to the wrong database, and the JSONB rows it returned
came from the wrong place. The Lakebase pool cache key includes
the effective database, so once the override was correctly
plumbed everywhere else, this was the *only* hole left.

Fix:
* ``src/back/objects/registry/RegistryService.py`` â€” pass
  ``database=cfg.lakebase_database`` when calling
  ``RegistryFactory.lakebase`` from ``_build_store``. The Volume
  branch is unchanged. Docstring updated to spell out why
  forgetting the override is a silent footgun.
* ``tests/test_registry_store.py`` â€” two new factory tests:
  ``test_lakebase_database_override_propagates_to_store`` checks
  that ``RegistryFactory.lakebase(database=...)`` surfaces the
  override on ``describe()`` and bakes it into ``cache_key``;
  ``test_lakebase_factory_for_backend_plumbs_database`` covers
  the higher-level ``for_backend`` and ``from_cfg`` entry points
  that ``_build_store`` would route through if the cfg ever
  carried the override pre-built.

Verification:
* ``uv run pytest`` â€” 1810 / 1810 pass (incl. 2 new tests).
* Linter clean on the touched files.
* Manual: with Lakebase selected and a database override set,
  Registry/Browse now reads from the chosen database (verified
  against the SP audit log on the bound instance â€” queries hit
  the override DB, not ``PGDATABASE``).

================================================================
[refactor] Decouple registry callers from the Volume backend
================================================================

Goal:
Make every registry read/write path honour the active backend
(``cfg.backend == "volume"`` vs ``"lakebase"``). The Lakebase
plumbing was already in place, but two paths still reached into
the Unity Catalog Volume directly and would silently produce
wrong results on Lakebase-only registries.

Findings (audit of every ``self._uc.*`` call in
``RegistryService.py`` and every ``VolumeFileService(...)``
construction site outside ``store/volume/``):

1. ``RegistryService.list_all_bridges`` â€” enumerated domains
   via ``self._uc.list_directory(self.domains_path(),
   dirs_only=True)``. On a Lakebase-only registry the on-Volume
   ``domains/`` folder may not exist, so the cross-domain
   bridge list silently returned empty. The per-domain ontology
   read inside the loop already went through the store via
   ``self.load_latest_domain_data`` â†’ ``self._store.read_version``
   (correct), only the *enumeration* was broken.
2. ``BuildScheduler._resolve_creds`` (used at app startup before
   the global config is loaded) â€” built a bare
   ``RegistryCfg(catalog, schema, volume)`` and dropped
   ``backend`` / ``lakebase_schema`` / ``lakebase_database``.
   Result: any schedule store call that fired before the first
   user opened the Schedule tab targeted Volume even on a
   Lakebase deployment with the Lakebase database resource
   bound. ``_resolve_creds`` is also the path the lazy
   ``_restore_jobs`` uses on cold start.

Other ``_uc.*`` call sites in ``RegistryService.py`` were
intentionally left as Volume-direct because they manipulate the
**binary tree only** â€” ``documents/`` and ``*.lbug.tar.gz``
always live on the Unity Catalog Volume regardless of which
:class:`RegistryStore` backs the registry. They are now grouped
under a single comment block that spells this contract out so
the next reader does not have to re-derive it. Affected
helpers (kept Volume-direct on purpose):
* ``_resolve_domains_folder`` / ``volume_root`` /
  ``domains_path`` / ``domain_path`` / ``version_path`` /
  ``version_file_path`` / ``marker_path`` /
  ``config_file_path`` / ``history_file_path``
* ``recursive_delete`` (binary tree wipe after
  ``store.delete_domain`` / ``store.delete_version``)
* ``copy_version_documents`` (per-version ``documents/`` copy)
* ``migrate_domain_layout`` (one-time flat â†’ versioned layout
  migration on the Volume)

External call sites also audited:
* ``DigitalTwin._backfill_registry_lbug`` and
  ``DigitalTwin._check_registry`` â€” read the Volume to check
  whether a registry ``.lbug.tar.gz`` archive exists. **Binary
  side, OK.**
* ``Domain.count_documents_in_volume`` â€” counts files in a
  version's ``documents/`` directory. **Binary side, OK.**
* ``Mapping.fetch_documents_for_agent`` â€” reads documents from
  a version's ``documents/`` directory. **Binary side, OK.**
* ``GraphDBFactory._build_auto_restore`` â€” restores ``.lbug``
  graphs from the Volume on first DT/Build access. **Binary
  side, OK.**
* ``home.read_volume_file`` /
  ``home.write_volume_file`` â€” generic UC Volume R/W endpoints
  that take an explicit path from the frontend. **Not
  registry-specific, OK.**
* ``UCDomainIO.list_domains`` /
  ``UCDomainIO.load_domain`` â€” public ``/api/v1/domain/...``
  REST endpoints that take an explicit ``domain_path`` and
  read JSON from the Volume. **Public REST surface explicitly
  Volume-keyed; not used by the Browse / Load Domain flow.
  Kept as-is.**

Fixes:
* ``src/back/objects/registry/RegistryService.py``
  - ``list_all_bridges``: enumerate via
    ``self._store.list_domain_folders()`` instead of
    ``self._uc.list_directory(self.domains_path(), ...)``.
  - Added a multi-line comment block on the ``# -- path
    builders`` section that documents the Volume-only intent
    of every helper that still touches ``self._uc`` directly,
    so the contract (binary artifacts always live on the
    Volume) is impossible to miss.
* ``src/back/objects/registry/scheduler.py``
  - ``_resolve_creds`` now reads ``settings.registry_backend``,
    ``settings.lakebase_schema`` and ``settings.lakebase_database``
    and forwards them to ``RegistryCfg``. Schedule reads/writes
    that fire before the global config is loaded (cold-start
    job restore, first-time CRON tick) now target the right
    backend on Lakebase deployments.

Tests added:
* ``tests/test_registry.py``
  - ``TestListAllBridges.test_uses_store_list_domain_folders_not_volume``
    rigs ``_uc.list_directory`` to raise so a regression to the
    Volume-direct enumeration would explode loudly. Stubs
    ``store.list_domain_folders`` and ``load_latest_domain_data``
    to verify the bridge result is built end-to-end.
  - ``TestListAllBridges.test_skips_hidden_folder_names`` locks
    in the ``.hidden`` folder filter behaviour.
  - ``TestSchedulerResolveCredsBackend.test_volume_defaults`` and
    ``...test_lakebase_with_database_override`` cover the
    scheduler's startup credential resolution.

Verification:
* ``uv run pytest`` â€” **1814 / 1814 passed** (4 new tests).
* Linter clean on ``RegistryService.py``, ``scheduler.py``,
  and ``tests/test_registry.py``.
* Manual: with Lakebase selected and at least one domain
  carrying bridges, Registry/Browse â†’ "Bridges" now lists
  every domain's bridges. Previously the panel was empty
  unless the registry also happened to keep a ``domains/``
  folder on the Volume.

================================================================
2026-04-27 (late) â€” Settings â†’ Registry Location: unbreak the
                    backend chooser on Databricks Apps
================================================================

Summary:
On any Databricks Apps deployment a Volume resource is bound to
the app, so ``SettingsService.is_registry_locked()`` returns
``True``. The lock was originally meant to protect the bound
``catalog/schema/volume`` triplet from being silently desynced
by an in-app edit â€” but it was *also* disabling the **backend
radios** in Settings â†’ Registry Location and rejecting any POST
to ``/settings/registry``. Net result: admins on a deployed app
could never flip Volume â†” Lakebase from the UI, even when the
``database`` resource was correctly bound and Lakebase was
fully available (``psycopg_installed: true, env_ready: true,
bound: true``). The whole purpose of the runtime backend toggle
was being defeated by an over-eager safety net.

Two surgical changes restore the intended UX:

1. **JS** â€” ``updateBackendChooser`` now disables the Lakebase
   radio purely on availability, and the Volume radio is always
   enabled. The lock no longer leaks into the chooser.

2. **API** â€” ``POST /settings/registry`` no longer hard-fails
   when locked. It only refuses *non-empty* writes to
   ``catalog/schema/volume`` (the bound triplet) and lets
   ``backend``, ``lakebase_schema``, and ``lakebase_database``
   through unchanged. Empty values for the locked keys are
   silently stripped (some clients echo the full config back).

The ``app.yaml`` extra fix earlier the same day (uv run with
``--extra lakebase``) is what makes this practically useful:
Postgres-side deps are now always present in the running
container, so flipping to Lakebase Just Works the moment the
database resource binding goes live â€” no redeploy required.

Files changed:
* ``src/front/static/registry/js/registry.js``
  - ``updateBackendChooser``: drop ``registryLocked`` from the
    radio-disabled equation. Comment block records *why* the
    lock semantic is intentionally narrow.
* ``src/api/routers/internal/settings.py``
  - ``save_registry``: read the body first, then on lock
    intersect against the locked-keys set. Raise only when a
    non-empty write to a locked key is attempted; otherwise
    forward a sanitised payload to ``apply_registry_save``.
    Updated docstring to spell out the contract.

Tests added:
* ``tests/test_registry.py::TestSaveRegistryRouteLockedSemantics``
  - ``test_locked_blocks_catalog_schema_volume_changes``: a
    write to ``{"catalog": "evil"}`` on a locked deployment
    raises ``ValidationError`` and never reaches
    ``apply_registry_save``.
  - ``test_locked_allows_backend_switch``: ``{"backend":
    "lakebase"}`` on a locked deployment is forwarded
    unchanged.
  - ``test_locked_allows_lakebase_database_override``:
    ``lakebase_database`` + ``lakebase_schema`` are accepted on
    a locked deployment.
  - ``test_locked_strips_locked_keys_silently_when_empty``: a
    payload echoing ``{"catalog": "", "schema": "", "backend":
    "lakebase"}`` is silently sanitised to just ``{"backend":
    "lakebase"}`` â€” no exception.
  - ``test_unlocked_passes_payload_through``: on an unlocked
    deployment the full payload is forwarded as-is.

Verification:
* ``uv run --extra lakebase pytest tests/test_registry.py
  tests/test_registry_store.py`` â€” **92 / 92 passed**.
* Manual (deployed dev app, ``ontobricks-dev``):
  - ``GET /settings/registry`` returns ``available_backends.lakebase
    = {available: true, psycopg_installed: true, env_ready:
    true}`` and ``lakebase.bound = true`` with the
    ``ontobricks-app`` instance details populated.
  - With ``registry_locked: true`` (Volume is bound by DAB), the
    Lakebase radio is now selectable in **Settings â†’ Registry
    Location**, and switching backend persists via
    ``POST /settings/registry``.

================================================================
2026-04-27 (later) â€” Backend switch silently reverted to Volume
                     on Databricks Apps deployments
================================================================

Summary:
After re-enabling the backend chooser earlier today, switching
to Lakebase from Settings â†’ Registry Location appeared to
succeed (``POST /settings/registry`` returned 200) but the next
``GET /settings/registry`` came back with ``backend: "volume"``,
silently flipping the radio back. The persisted value was
correct in ``domain.settings.registry.backend``; what was
broken was the *read path*.

``RegistryCfg.from_domain`` had a fast-path: when
``settings.registry_volume_path`` is set (i.e. on every
Databricks Apps deployment, because the Volume resource is
bound) it short-circuited to ``from_volume_path`` and read the
backend choice **only** from ``settings.registry_backend``
(env var). The carefully-saved ``domain.settings.registry``
override was never consulted on that branch. Same trap for
``lakebase_schema`` / ``lakebase_database``: any UI override
would be discarded on the next read.

Fix: layer ``domain.settings.registry`` *over* the env values
**before** picking the branch, so the bound-Volume path still
sources catalog/schema/volume from the resource binding (which
must always win) but the **backend** and **Lakebase-side
knobs** carry the admin's UI choice through both paths.

Files changed:
* ``src/back/objects/registry/RegistryService.py``
  - ``RegistryCfg.from_domain``: rewrite the resolution order.
    Read ``domain.settings.registry`` first; ``backend``,
    ``lakebase_schema`` and ``lakebase_database`` resolve to
    the session value with env as a fallback. Pass them into
    both the bound-volume path (``from_volume_path``) and the
    legacy / local-dev path. Updated the docstring with the
    explicit precedence order.

Tests added:
* ``tests/test_registry.py::TestRegistryCfgConstruction``
  - ``test_from_domain_volume_path_keeps_session_backend``: a
    bound-Volume deployment with ``domain.settings.registry =
    {"backend": "lakebase"}`` returns ``backend == "lakebase"``
    even when the env says Volume â€” proves the radio choice
    survives the round-trip.
  - ``test_from_domain_volume_path_keeps_session_lakebase_overrides``:
    ``lakebase_schema`` / ``lakebase_database`` UI overrides
    survive on the bound-Volume path.
  - ``test_from_domain_no_volume_path_session_backend_wins``:
    same precedence on the local-dev path, locking down the
    behaviour for both code paths.

Verification:
* ``uv run --extra lakebase pytest tests/test_registry.py
  tests/test_registry_store.py`` â€” **95 / 95 passed** (3 new).
* Linter clean on ``RegistryService.py`` and the test file.
* Manual (deployed ``ontobricks-dev``): Settings â†’ Registry
  Location â†’ Lakebase radio + Save â†’ ``GET /settings/registry``
  reports ``backend == "lakebase"`` and the Lakebase panel
  populates with the bound instance/database/schema, instead
  of snapping back to Volume.

================================================================
2026-04-27 (v3) â€” *Migrate to Lakebase* button vanished after
                  the very flip that needed it
================================================================

Summary:
After flipping to the Lakebase backend on a fresh deployment
the inventory grid showed "0 rows" for every table â€” which is
correct, the schema is genuinely empty â€” but the **Migrate to
Lakebase** button was hidden and the admin had no way to
populate it. The button visibility condition was
``backend === 'volume'``, which made the button vanish the
moment the radio flipped to Lakebase. Net result: switching
backend was a one-way trap with empty tables on the other
side.

Fix:
1. ``_lakebase_runtime_info`` now includes an ``initialized``
   boolean (``store.is_initialized()`` probe). The probe is
   best-effort, never raises, and is gated on the optional
   ``psycopg`` extra. Added a sister method
   ``_lakebase_schema_initialized`` to keep the probe out of
   the main runtime-info path.
2. JS shows **Migrate to Lakebase** when:
   - Lakebase is available (``psycopg`` + bound resource), AND
   - the Volume registry is configured, AND
   - either the admin is still on Volume, OR Lakebase is
     selected but ``lakebase.initialized`` is ``false``.
   The "still on Volume" branch keeps the pre-switch flow
   (admins can pre-warm Lakebase before flipping); the new
   "selected but uninitialised" branch is the rescue path.

Files changed:
* ``src/back/objects/domain/SettingsService.py``
  - ``_lakebase_runtime_info``: include
    ``initialized: bool``; the existing payload is otherwise
    unchanged.
  - ``_lakebase_schema_initialized`` (new helper): build a
    Lakebase store via ``RegistryFactory`` and call
    ``is_initialized()``. Catches every exception (including
    ``ImportError`` on Volume-only stacks) and returns
    ``False`` â€” the field is purely informational.
* ``src/front/static/registry/js/registry.js``
  - ``updateBackendChooser``: replace
    ``backend === 'volume'`` with the more nuanced rule
    above; comment block records the rationale.

Verification:
* ``uv run --extra lakebase pytest tests/test_registry.py
  tests/test_registry_store.py`` â€” **95 / 95 passed**.
* Linter clean.
* Manual (deployed ``ontobricks-dev``):
  - On Volume â†’ button visible. âś“
  - On Lakebase + empty schema â†’ button visible (the rescue
    path). âś“
  - On Lakebase + initialised schema â†’ button hidden so the
    admin doesn't accidentally re-migrate over live data. âś“

================================================================
2026-04-27 (v4) â€” DAB Lakebase resource binding: Autoscaling
                  uses the wrong schema (branch missing,
                  database name landed in the wrong field)
================================================================

Summary:
The ``dev-lakebase`` target was wiring the Lakebase resource
with the **Provisioned-tier** YAML schema:

```yaml
- name: database
  database:
    database_name: ontobricks_registry
    instance_name: ontobricks-app
    permission: CAN_CONNECT_AND_CREATE
```

But Lakebase instances created after 2026-03-12 are
**Autoscaling projects**, which require an entirely different
schema: ``postgres: { branch, database }`` where both fields
are *full project-relative resource paths* (e.g.
``projects/ontobricks-app/branches/production`` and
``projects/ontobricks-app/branches/production/databases/db-xxx-yyy``).

When the bundle reached the Apps platform with the wrong
schema the bind was technically accepted but visibly mangled in
the UI (database name landed in the *branch* field) and the
runtime PG env-var injection was unstable. The dev sandbox
``ontobricks-app`` is an Autoscaling project â€” the project's
default branch is ``production`` (NOT ``main``), and the
``ontobricks_registry`` database has resource ID
``db-8u4l-0na72ub5sp``.

Fix:
1. Replaced the ``dev-lakebase`` binding with the Autoscaling
   ``postgres`` schema, populated from new variables
   (``lakebase_branch``, ``lakebase_database_resource``) so the
   admin can override resource paths without editing the YAML.
2. Added a sibling ``dev-lakebase-provisioned`` target that
   keeps the legacy Provisioned schema for instances that still
   pre-date the Autoscaling rollout.
3. Variable docs spell out the lookup recipe via
   ``databricks api get
   /api/2.0/postgres/projects/<project>/branches/<branch>/databases``
   so the next admin can pick a different database without
   re-deriving the resource path from scratch.

Files changed:
* ``databricks.yml``
  - New variables ``lakebase_branch`` and
    ``lakebase_database_resource`` with descriptive defaults
    matching the dev sandbox.
  - ``dev-lakebase``: rewritten to use the Autoscaling
    ``postgres`` resource (default key) with full resource
    paths.
  - ``dev-lakebase-provisioned``: new sibling target that
    keeps the legacy Provisioned binding alive for
    backwards-compat.
  - Comment block at the top of the variable section
    documents the schema split, the post-2026-03-12
    Autoscaling default, and the silent-misroute failure
    mode.

Verification:
* ``databricks bundle validate -t dev-lakebase`` â€” clean.
* ``databricks bundle deploy -t dev-lakebase`` â€” succeeded.
* ``databricks bundle run ontobricks_dev_app -t dev-lakebase``
  â€” app restarted in 212s, status RUNNING/ACTIVE.
* ``databricks apps get ontobricks-dev``: the bound resource
  now reports::

      "postgres": {
        "branch": "projects/ontobricks-app/branches/production",
        "database": "projects/ontobricks-app/branches/production/databases/db-8u4l-0na72ub5sp",
        "permission": "CAN_CONNECT_AND_CREATE"
      }

* ``GET /settings/registry`` from the deployed dev app:
  ``lakebase.bound = true``, ``effective_database =
  ontobricks_registry``, ``schema = ontobricks_registry``,
  ``initialized = false`` (next step: click *Migrate to
  Lakebase* to populate the empty schema).
* Production ``ontobricks`` app â€” untouched (this DAB only
  manages ``ontobricks-dev``).


## Lakebase registry identity = the schema (decouple from Volume path)

Context: deployed apps with the Lakebase backend reported
``initialized: false`` and "0 rows in every table" even though the
Postgres schema had been migrated end-to-end. Root cause: the
``LakebaseRegistryStore`` keyed the ``registries.name`` row by the
*Volume* triplet (``catalog.schema.volume``). When two apps shared a
Lakebase but were bound to different Volumes (typical of an
``ontobricks-dev`` sandbox running next to the prod ``ontobricks``
app), the dev app could not find the registry row created by prod â€”
and a brand-new row would never be inserted because the first
``is_initialized()`` probe is read-only. Switching the UI backend to
*Lakebase (Postgres)* should map directly to the bound Lakebase
configuration (instance + database + schema) â€” the Volume binding
is incidental, only used for binary artifacts. This change makes
that the contract.

Changes:

1. src/back/objects/registry/store/lakebase/store.py
   ``_registry_name()`` now returns ``self._schema``: the Postgres
   schema *is* the registry namespace. Two apps pointing at the same
   ``(instance, database, schema)`` triple share the registry; two
   apps on the same Lakebase but different schemas are isolated. The
   Volume triplet is intentionally absent from the identity.
   ``_fetch_registry_id()`` keeps backward-compat with pre-existing
   schemas via a "legacy adoption" path: when no row matches the new
   schema-keyed name but exactly one (or, with a warning, several)
   legacy row(s) live in this schema, the oldest is renamed in
   place. No data migration script needed â€” the first read in the
   deployed app self-heals the row.
   ``table_row_counts()`` and ``is_initialized()`` no longer swallow
   connection / permission errors silently; ``table_row_counts``
   propagates so the admin UI can surface a clear error instead of
   misleading all-zero rows.
   ``_LakebasePool`` / ``_get_pool()`` accept an optional
   ``database`` argument so admins can swap the Postgres database
   from the UI without redeploying (JWT scope is per-instance, so
   the cached token still authenticates).
   New ``_effective_database`` property + ``database_override`` /
   ``effective_database`` keys in the runtime payload.

2. tests/test_registry_store.py
   New ``TestLakebaseRegistryIdentity`` covering the four cases:
   schema-as-name, hit-by-name, lone-legacy adoption, empty-schema
   no-op, multi-legacy oldest-wins. The multi-legacy test now
   patches ``logger.warning`` directly (avoids caplog brittleness
   when other tests reconfigure the root logger).
   New ``TestLakebaseTableRowCountsErrors`` pinning the new
   propagating-vs-zero contract.

3. tests/test_registry.py
   ``TestSaveRegistryRouteLockedSemantics`` now executes the
   coroutine via a worker-thread ``_run`` helper instead of the
   ``@pytest.mark.asyncio`` runner. Pytest-asyncio + anyio session
   loops occasionally cross-pollinate (``Runner.run() cannot be
   called from a running event loop``); a private
   ``new_event_loop()`` on a daemon thread keeps the case hermetic
   regardless of test ordering.

