## Lakebase JWT mint failed: PGAPPNAME is the app name, not the instance

Context: deployed ``ontobricks-dev`` raised
``Database instance 'ontobricks-dev' not found`` when trying to mint
a Lakebase JWT. The actual instance is ``ontobricks-app``. Root
cause: ``LakebaseAuth.instance_name`` consulted ``PGAPPNAME`` as a
fallback identifier, but ``PGAPPNAME`` is libpq's
``application_name`` (a free-form connection trace label), and the
Databricks Apps runtime populates it with the *app's* name. So
``generate_database_credential(instance_names=["ontobricks-dev"])``
was hitting a non-existent instance.

Changes:

1. src/back/core/databricks/LakebaseAuth.py
   Drop ``PGAPPNAME`` from the instance-name resolution chain.
   Order is now: ``DATABASE_INSTANCE_NAME`` env var â†’ SDK lookup
   matching ``PGHOST`` against ``read_write_dns`` /
   ``read_only_dns`` of the workspace's database instances. Module
   docstring updated to call out why ``PGAPPNAME`` is intentionally
   ignored.

2. tests/test_lakebase_auth.py (new)
   Five-case test class pinning the resolver: explicit env wins;
   ``PGAPPNAME`` is never used (regression for the deployed-app
   failure); SDK lookup matches host to ``read_write_dns``; result
   is cached; SDK failure surfaces as ``ValidationError``.

